            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~nazsco" class="author" title="author name and user ID">nazsco (695026) </a> | about 2 years ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=3148631&cid=41482259">(#41482259)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_41482259" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="1" data-reason="Normal">
            <div class="comment-body"><p>As someone who worked for firms working on bank security, i call tell you they remain silent about 100% of their electronic breaches and cover the money in silence. The reasoning is that lower accounts are their milking cow now, and news of some measly 200,000 robbed by electronic means (they lose more than that per day), while insignificant to the bank, would draw away those lesser accounts to whom 200,000 is a fortune. and draw away too many of the lesser accounts and the bank starts to be in real problem.</p><p>besides those in-the-dark screw ups, you also have the public ones. more recently bank of america showing other peoples each other account instead of their own and such.</p></div>
